      <hedline>
        <hl1>When Politics Is a Family Affair</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fred Polvere letter says Gov George W Bush's inability to prevail against more conservative Republicans on education agenda reflects poorly on his leadership abilities (July 29 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Republican Party's 2000 platform states that the role of the federal government in education ''must be progressively limited'' (news article, July 29). This is at odds with the agenda put forth by Gov. George W. Bush, the party's presidential candidate.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Republican Party's 2000 platform states that the role of the federal government in education ''must be progressively limited'' (news article, July 29). This is at odds with the agenda put forth by Gov. George W. Bush, the party's presidential candidate.</p>
        <p>I wonder how Governor Bush will be able to lead a divided Congress and a diverse country when he cannot seem to prevail against the more conservative elements in his own party.</p>
        <p>FRED POLVERE  Yonkers, July 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
